# Devscrolls UI foundation (mandatory for user-visible UI)

For **any** user-visible work—components, layout, typography, marketing pages, dashboards, forms, chrome—**unless** the product owner explicitly asked for a **different** brand or white-label aesthetic:

1. Read **`DESIGN.md`** at the **repository root** (synced from **`scrolls-cf/scrollsdesigner`**) and follow its non-negotiables, **including brand personality** and **#11** (no modal overlays or `window.alert` / `confirm` / `prompt` unless explicitly asked). Fleet changes: **`scrolls-cf/scrollsdesigner`** → **`npm run sync:fleet`** (`patterns/goldpath/fleet-design-evolve-in-scrollsdesigner-first.md` in scrollsdesigner).
2. Keep a fleet theme on the shell (default **`data-theme="devscrolls"`**). Tokens live in **`themes/`**. Do not invent parallel color systems.
3. Use **DaisyUI semantic colors** and **stock components** (v5 patterns) per `DESIGN.md`; prefer **Tailwind utilities** for layout. **Minimize custom CSS** that duplicates Daisy/Tailwind—see **`DESIGN.md`** non-negotiable **#10**, [`patterns/goldpath/daisyui-tailwind-minimal-drift.md`](patterns/goldpath/daisyui-tailwind-minimal-drift.md), and [`patterns/goldpath/daisyui-5-form-fields-markup.md`](patterns/goldpath/daisyui-5-form-fields-markup.md) (inputs, textareas, multi-line UX). Do not default to raw Tailwind palette colors for text or surfaces.
4. For motion, still follow **`docs/gsap-for-agents.md`** and **`patterns/goldpath/gsap-prefer-transforms.md`**.
5. **Brand / marketing / UX-UI agents** make **design choices** inside the tokens above. **Internal / tool UI** uses efficient, literal labels (`DESIGN.md` #9). **Fleet-wide** token/theme updates: edit **`scrolls-cf/scrollsdesigner`**, run **`npm run sync:fleet`**. Product-only CSS: **`src/styles/product.css`** in this repo.

If the task is explicitly **another brand**, **client design system**, or **importing an external `DESIGN.md`**, read **`docs/design-md-for-agents.md`** and **`patterns/goldpath/design-md-brand-ui.md`** and reconcile conflicts with the product owner—do not silently override the fleet foundation.
